Encodes for CSS strings. The context must be surrounded by quotation characters. It is safe for use in both style blocks and attributes in HTML. Example JSP Usage      ');">


         background: url('');

 Encoding Notes The following characters are encoded using hexidecimal encodings: {@code U+0000} - {@code U+001f}, {@code "}, {@code '}, {@code \}, {@code }, {@code U+007f}, line separator ({@code U+2028}), paragraph separator ({@code U+2029}). Any character requiring encoding is encoded as {@code \xxx} where {@code xxx} is the shortest hexidecimal representation of its Unicode code point (after decoding surrogate pairs if necessary). This encoding is never zero padded. Thus, for example, the tab character is encoded as {@code \9}, not {@code \0009}. The encoder looks ahead 1 character in the input and appends a space to an encoding to avoid the next character becoming part of the hexidecimal encoded sequence. Thus “{@code '1}” is encoded as “{@code \27 1}”, and not as “{@code \271}”. If a space is not necessary, it is not included, thus “{@code 'x}” is encoded as “{@code \27x}”, and not as “{@code \27 x}”. Surrogate pairs are passed through only if valid. Invalid surrogate pairs are replaced by an underscore (_). Unicode "non-characters" are replaced by underscores (_).

