This method encodes for JavaScript strings contained within a JavaScript or JSON file. This method is NOT safe for use in ANY context embedded in HTML. The caller must provide the surrounding quotation characters. This method performs the same encode as {@link #forJavaScript(String)} with the exception that / and & are not escaped and " and ' are encoded as \" and \' respectively. Unless you are interested in saving a few bytes of output or are writing a framework on top of this library, it is recommend that you use {@link #forJavaScript(String)} over this method. Example JSP Usage: This example is serving up JavaScript source directly:     
    var data = "";
 This example is serving up JSON data (users of this use-case are encouraged to read up on "JSON Hijacking"):     

    {"data":""}
